      "The dive watch as we know it was born in 1953, a banner year that produced two of the genre's founding fathers almost simultaneously. Blancpain's Fifty Fathoms, championed by CEO and avid diver Jean-Jacques Fiechter (and developed in dialogue with French combat divers Bob Maloubier and Claude Riffaud), is widely credited as the first modern dive watch. It codified the recipe: a unidirectional rotating timing bezel, high water resistance (50 fathoms, about 91.5 m), a high-contrast luminous dial, antimagnetic protection, and automatic winding. That same year Rolex finalized the Submariner (reference 6204), shown to the public at the 1954 Basel fair and guaranteed waterproof to 100 m — going one better than the Fifty Fathoms on depth. Between them, these two watches set the template every diver since has followed.",
