      "Two other houses defined the genre alongside Patek. Cartier had been thinking about elegant wrist-worn time even earlier — the Santos of 1904, built for aviator Alberto Santos-Dumont, is widely regarded as the first purpose-built men's wristwatch. Then in 1917 Louis Cartier designed the Tank, its rectangular case and vertical 'brancards' said to be inspired by the overhead silhouette of a Renault FT-17 tank. With Roman numerals, sword hands, and a single sapphire cabochon set in the crown, the Tank became the most culturally significant shaped dress watch in history, worn by figures from Jacqueline Kennedy to Andy Warhol, who quipped that it was simply 'the watch to wear.' It proves an important point: a dress watch need not be round.",
