    goodToKnow: [
      'The single most important enthusiast distinction is true/flyer GMT vs. caller/office GMT. A TRUE (a.k.a. flyer or traveler) GMT lets you jump the LOCAL hour hand independently in one-hour steps while home time keeps running on the 24-hour hand—ideal for actually flying somewhere. A CALLER (a.k.a. office) GMT instead lets you set the 24-HOUR hand independently while the local hand stays put—great for tracking a relative or office abroad from home, less convenient when you travel.',
      "Quick tell for which type you have: with a true GMT the local hour hand jumps in 1-hour clicks via the crown; with a caller GMT it's the 24-hour hand that's independently adjustable. The famous true GMTs (Rolex GMT-Master II, Tudor Black Bay GMT) jump the local hand; many affordable ones (Seiko 4R34/NH34) are callers.",
      "The Miyota 9075 (2022) is significant because it was one of the first affordable movements to offer TRUE/flyer GMT functionality, whereas the popular Seiko 4R34/NH34 of the same era is a caller—so two sub-$1,000 watches can both say 'GMT' yet behave completely differently.",
      "A GMT shows two time zones; a worldtimer shows all 24 simultaneously. They solve related problems with very different mechanisms—don't conflate them. The worldtimer mechanism traces almost entirely to one man, Louis Cottier, in the early 1930s.",
      "Strictly, the colored hand reads UTC/your reference zone, not necessarily 'GMT'—Greenwich Mean Time and Coordinated Universal Time differ in definition though they coincide in practice. The 'GMT' name is a holdover from the aviation era and is now used loosely for the whole 24-hour-hand genre.",
      "On a Rolex GMT-Master (pre-GMT-Master II) the hour hand was NOT independent—setting local time dragged the 24-hour hand with it via the bezel. The independent quickset hour hand only arrived with the caliber 3085 GMT-Master II in 1982, which is exactly why Rolex created the 'II' designation.",
      "Rolex didn't invent the 24-hour-hand wristwatch—Glycine's Airman beat the GMT-Master to market by about a year (1953 vs. 1954), a fact snobs love to drop.",
    ],
