    tagline:
      'Watches that swap a solid dial for a window into the machine — from a single peephole over the balance wheel to a movement carved down to lace.',
    history: [
      "The idea of showing the movement is older than the wristwatch itself. Around 1760, the Parisian watchmaker Andre-Charles Caron is generally credited with the first skeletonized pocket watch: he removed the dial and cut away the metal of the movement so the mechanism itself became the decoration. Caron worked in the orbit of Jean-Antoine Lepine, the man whose calibre layout of thin bridges and plates (the 'Lepine calibre' of the 1760s) underpins almost every watch since — and who married Caron's daughter, becoming his son-in-law and business partner. These first skeletons were objects for the nobility: every wheel, bridge and barrel was sawn, filed and hand-engraved one piece at a time, often dressed with floral motifs, turning a functional object into a piece of jewelry.",
      "For two centuries skeletonization stayed a niche craft flex — a way for a maison to prove its hand-finishing chops. The genre got a modern, mainstream identity in two waves. First, ultra-thin houses like Piaget and Vacheron Constantin showed that openworking could be married to thinness and high complication; Piaget's micro-rotor Caliber 1200S became one of the thinnest automatic skeleton movements in the world. Second, the 2000s brought a louder, sportier reinterpretation — most visibly Roger Dubuis, whose Excalibur line (launched 2005) built an entire brand identity around its star-shaped skeleton bridge and Poincon de Geneve finishing, and Audemars Piguet, which has openworked the Royal Oak on and off since the 1930s and turned 'Openworked' into a permanent catalogue word.",
      "The 'open-heart' branch is largely a 20th-21st century, Japanese-led democratization of the same instinct. Rather than gut the whole movement, you cut a single window — usually over the balance wheel — so a wearer can watch the heartbeat oscillate while keeping a normal, legible dial. Frederique Constant popularized the look in the affordable-luxury space with its 'Heart Beat' models, and Seiko made it a global entry point: the Presage 'Cocktail Time' line, which started in Japan in 2010 (ref. SARB065) and went global with the Presage relaunch in 2017, gained dedicated Open Heart models in 2021 powered by the in-house automatic Caliber 4R38, with a cutout at 9 o'clock revealing the balance from the dial side.",
      "Today the category spans an enormous range. At one end is a sub-$500 Seiko showing you a single beating balance; at the other are six-figure haute horlogerie pieces where the movement was conceived from a blank sheet to be seen from every angle. Crucially, the vocabulary has split: purists now distinguish 'skeletonizing/openworking' (modifying an existing movement by cutting metal away) from movements 'designed open' from the start — and from the milder 'open-heart' peephole. All three sell the same fantasy: time you can watch being made.",
    ],
    popularity:
      "A genuinely cross-tier style. At the affordable end it is hugely popular with beginners and gift-buyers — the open-heart Seiko Presage and Frederique Constant Heart Beat are classic 'first mechanical watch' choices because the visible balance wheel makes the romance of automatic watchmaking obvious at a glance. In the middle, brands like Tissot, Hamilton, Rado and Oris use skeletons as design statements. At the top, openworking is a flex of finishing and engineering prowess, central to the identities of Roger Dubuis, Audemars Piguet, Vacheron Constantin, Cartier (Prive) and Richard Mille. Among hardcore enthusiasts opinion splits: snobs love a properly hand-anglaged, sawn-by-hand skeleton as a showcase of craft, but are quick to sneer at cheap quartz 'skeletons' with printed-on detail or a movement that was designed open and merely looks busy. Legibility skeptics also note these watches trade time-telling clarity for spectacle. The trend at recent Watches & Wonders fairs has been strongly toward openworked and skeletonized releases across the industry.",
