    goodToKnow: [
      "'Open-heart' and 'skeleton' are not the same thing. Open-heart = a single window (usually over the balance) in an otherwise normal dial. Skeleton = the dial is gone and the movement's bridges/plates are cut away. Calling an open-heart Seiko a 'skeleton' will get you corrected on the forums.",
      "Purists also separate 'skeletonized/openworked' (verbs — material was removed from an existing movement by hand) from movements 'designed open' from the start. The traditional craft is the former: holes are drilled, a tiny handsaw blade is threaded through, and the metal is cut out by hand, then files erase the saw marks.",
      "Open-working has limits — you can't just cut everywhere. The watchmaker must leave enough metal around jewel beds, screws and the gear train, or the movement loses rigidity and reliability. Knowing where NOT to cut is the skill.",
      'Skeletonizing is brutally labor-intensive: interior angles (where two bevels meet at an acute point) must be done entirely by hand, and a single tricky part can take around ten hours to finish. That hand-labor is most of what you pay for at the high end.',
      "Legibility is the genre's built-in weakness — hands disappear into the busy backdrop. Good designs solve it with a contrasting chapter ring and high-contrast hands; bad ones just look like a pretty mess.",
      "Beware the fake flex: many cheap 'skeleton' watches use a movement that was designed open (or even a quartz module with decorative plates) rather than one painstakingly hand-cut. Real skeletonization shows hand-anglage and engraving under a loupe; printed or stamped 'detail' does not.",
      "It's one of horology's oldest party tricks: the first skeleton pocket watches date to around 1760 (Andre-Charles Caron), nearly the same moment Lepine was inventing the thin bridge-and-plate calibre that made showing the movement attractive in the first place.",
    ],
