    title: 'Automatic (Self-Winding) Movements',
    tagline:
      'A weighted rotor turns the motion of your wrist into a wound mainspring — the do-nothing-and-it-runs default of modern mechanical watchmaking.',
    history: [
      'An automatic (or "self-winding") movement is a mechanical watch that winds its own mainspring using a rotor — a semicircular weight, usually a dense metal such as brass or tungsten, mounted on a pivot at the center of the movement. As your wrist moves through the day, the rotor swings on its bearing and, through a reduction gear train, tightens the mainspring. The barrel stores that energy and releases it in tiny, regulated pulses via the escapement, exactly as in a hand-wound watch. The only real difference from a manual movement is the automatic winding mechanism added on top of the gear train; strip the rotor assembly off and you have essentially a hand-wound caliber underneath, which is why automatics are inherently a bit thicker than manuals.',
      'The idea is older than the wristwatch. Swiss watchmaker Abraham-Louis Perrelet is generally credited with a self-winding pocket-watch mechanism around 1777, and Abraham-Louis Breguet built celebrated "perpetuelle" self-winders shortly after. But a pocket watch barely moves, so those early efforts were impractical. The breakthrough belonged to the wristwatch, which is in constant motion. In 1923 English watchmaker John Harwood patented the first practical automatic wristwatch — a "bumper" design whose weight swung between two buffer springs across an arc rather than a full circle. The decisive leap came in 1931, when Rolex introduced the Oyster Perpetual with a rotor that swung a full 360 degrees, the basis of nearly every automatic since. Rolex\'s marketing turned the word "Perpetual" into shorthand for self-winding.',
      'Two later refinements defined the modern automatic. In 1948 Eterna launched the Eterna-Matic, mounting the rotor on five tiny ball bearings (the inspiration for the five dots in the Eterna and later Eterna/Eterna-Matic logo) instead of a friction-prone plain bushing — a huge gain in reliability and a big reduction in wear. Ball-bearing rotors are now standard. The other refinement was efficient bidirectional winding, which captures energy whether the rotor spins clockwise or counter-clockwise: Rolex\'s pawl-based system and, later, clever low-cost solutions such as Seiko\'s "Magic Lever" pawl-lever mechanism (used in the 7S/4R/NH families) made automatics both efficient and cheap to build.',
      'By the 1960s the automatic was the prestige default, and the race for an automatic chronograph produced a famous 1969 dead heat between the Zenith El Primero, the Seiko 6139, and the Chronomatic consortium (Heuer-Breitling-Hamilton/Buren-Dubois Depraz) Caliber 11. The Quartz Crisis of the 1970s-80s nearly wiped out mechanical watchmaking, but the mechanical revival from the 1990s onward — led by Swatch Group-owned ETA, independent Sellita, and the Japanese giants Seiko and Citizen/Miyota — cemented the automatic as the heart of the modern enthusiast watch. Today a self-winding movement is what most buyers mean when they say they want "a mechanical watch."',
    ],
    popularity:
      "The automatic is the default movement of the modern mechanical watch and the one most enthusiasts gravitate to. It carries more romance than quartz — a transparent caseback showing a decorated rotor sweeping back and forth is a core part of the hobby's appeal — without the daily ritual (or the fragility) of a hand-wound watch. Virtually every mainstream mechanical brand, from microbrands on a Seiko NH35 to Rolex and Patek Philippe in-house calibers, builds its core line around automatics. Among hobbyist watchmakers and modders, the Seiko NH35 and Miyota 8215/9015 are the universal starting points because they are cheap, abundant, and have a huge aftermarket of cases, dials, and hands. The main trade-offs buyers weigh are accuracy (a good automatic runs roughly -10 to +30 seconds/day stock, far worse than quartz), the need to wear or wind it every couple of days or reset it after it stops, and price — mechanical complexity costs more than a quartz module doing the same job more accurately.",
