    identifyingFeatures: [
      'Translucent or subtly textured dial that lets light through to the photovoltaic cell beneath — on cheaper or vintage pieces you can sometimes see a faint segmented or honeycomb pattern under the dial surface',
      'A power-reserve or charge indicator: many solar models add a small sub-dial or hand showing remaining charge, or a marker scale (H/M/L) for charge level',
      "An insufficient-charge warning behavior — e.g. classic Eco-Drive seconds hands jump in two-second steps when the cell runs low, signaling 'expose me to light'",
      'No visible winding rotor or balance wheel — the caseback is typically solid quartz-style; there is no automatic-rotor whir or audible mechanical tick, just the one-step-per-second stepper motion',
      'A sealed, change-free power system: marketing or caseback text referencing a rechargeable secondary cell or capacitor rather than a replaceable battery hatch',
      'Thin overall case profile relative to mechanicals, since the movement is quartz with a flat cell and panel rather than a stack of gears and a mainspring barrel',
      'On high-spec versions, antennae and labeling for radio (atomic) or GPS time-setting, since solar power is commonly bundled with self-setting timekeeping',
    ],
    goodToKnow: [
      "Capacitor vs. rechargeable cell is the connoisseur's distinction. Many 'solar' watches store energy in a lithium-type secondary (rechargeable) cell — Citizen Eco-Drive famously uses a titanium lithium-ion cell — while others, including several Seiko Solar V-series calibers, use a manganese-titanium-lithium rechargeable capacitor. Capacitors tolerate full discharge and heat better and have very long shelf lives; lithium cells store more energy for a given size but degrade faster if repeatedly run flat.",
      "The storage cell is not immortal, but it lasts a very long time. Citizen cites secondary cells lasting up to around 40 years and lab tests showing roughly 80% capacity retained after 20 years. Real-world experience suggests many solar cells need replacement somewhere in the 10–20+ year range — far longer than a standard quartz battery, but not literally 'forever.'",
      'Overcharge protection is built in. You cannot harm a quality solar watch by leaving it in the light; the circuit stops charging once the cell is full, so the surplus light energy is simply not stored.',
      "Total darkness reserves are generous: typical Eco-Drive men's models run about six months fully charged in the dark, and some calibers are rated far longer. Seiko's V157/V158 can run up to roughly ten months on a full charge.",
      'It charges from any light, not just sun. Indoor and fluorescent lighting work too, just much more slowly — a few minutes of strong sunlight can equal hours under a desk lamp, which is why daily wear under normal lighting is usually enough to keep one topped up.',
      'Common pitfalls: storing a solar watch for months in a dark drawer or wearing it under long sleeves can let it run down, and a permanently dead, never-recharged solar watch can over-discharge its cell. Keeping it in light, and giving it an occasional good charge, preserves long-term cell health.',
      'Solar is a power source, not a timekeeping standard. The oscillator is still standard quartz, so a basic solar watch is about as accurate as any quartz (a few seconds a month) — accuracy gains come from better quartz, radio/GPS syncing, or thermo-compensation, not from the solar cell itself.',
    ],
