    popularity:
      "\"'Swiss Made' is the single most powerful country-of-origin label in consumer goods, and it spans the entire wrist. At the bottom, Tissot, Hamilton, Certina and Swatch put genuine Swiss movements on beginners' wrists for a few hundred dollars. In the middle sit the aspirational icons — Tudor, Longines, TAG Heuer, Oris and Omega — the watches most enthusiasts actually own. At the top, Rolex is the global status benchmark, while the 'Holy Trinity' of Patek Philippe, Audemars Piguet and Vacheron Constantin define haute horlogerie for collectors. Culturally, a Swiss mechanical watch is the default 'serious watch' gift (graduations, retirements, milestones) and the anchor of a multi-billion-dollar resale and auction market. Current trends: integrated-bracelet sports-luxury steel pieces (the Royal Oak / Nautilus / Tissot PRX lineage) remain hot, independents and in-house movements command growing premiums, and value continues to concentrate at the high end — luxury pieces are a tiny share of units but the overwhelming share of export value and growth.\"",
