    identifyingFeatures: [
      "Spring Drive gliding seconds hand: a perfectly smooth, continuous sweep (no ticks, no semi-stutter) — the visual fingerprint of Seiko's quartz-regulated mechanical hybrid, often paired with a power-reserve indicator on the dial.",
      "Zaratsu mirror polishing and 'Grammar of Design' case work: flat, razor-sharp facets and distortion-free mirror surfaces on the case and hands that throw crisp, undistorted reflections (Grand Seiko hallmark).",
      "G-Shock's protective architecture: thick resin or metal bezel/case with recessed buttons, a bumper/guard around the display, screw-back or floating-module construction, and 200m water resistance — built for impact, not elegance.",
      'Translucent solar dial: Eco-Drive (and Seiko/Casio solar) watches use a slightly textured, light-passing dial with a photocell beneath it; no separate battery hatch since the cell recharges internally.',
      "Honest value-automatic signatures: exhibition casebacks showing a Seiko 4R/6R or Miyota/Orient rotor, day-date at 3 o'clock, and applied indices — common on Seiko 5 and Orient, where mechanical content is offered at low cost.",
      'Hi-beat and high-reserve mechanicals: Grand Seiko 9S calibers beat at 28,800 bph (some hi-beat at 36,000) with 72-hour reserves and tolerances measured in thousandths of a millimeter.',
      'LCD digital module with multi-function readout: the Casio idiom — segmented LCD, mode/light buttons, stopwatch, alarm and (on radio/solar models) atomic time-sync and world time.',
    ],
    goodToKnow: [
      "Spring Drive is neither pure quartz nor pure mechanical: a mainspring provides all the power, but a quartz crystal and an electromagnetic brake (the 'Tri-Synchro Regulator') govern a glide wheel spinning 8x per second — yielding ~+/-1 sec/day accuracy and a truly continuous seconds sweep. Engineer Yoshikazu Akahane chased it for ~28 years and 600+ prototypes before it matured in 2005.",
      "'Zaratsu' is a phonetic Japanese rendering of 'Sallaz,' the German Sallaz-type lapping machines imported in the mid-20th century. The technique presses the case against the flat face of a rotating tin/abrasive plate (not a soft buffing wheel), which is what produces the distortion-free, almost liquid-looking mirror — and it's still done by hand by a small number of trained craftspeople.",
      "Citizen's Miyota arm reportedly makes on the order of 100 million movements a year — roughly three per second — making it one of the largest movement manufacturers on earth. The workhorse Miyota 8215 (since 1977) and the slimmer, higher-spec 9015 (2009) power countless microbrand and fashion watches you'd never guess were Citizen inside.",
      "Casio funded its way into watches as a calculator company (founded 1946); the 'G' in G-Shock stands for gravity, and inventor Kikuo Ibe's breakthrough came from watching kids bounce a rubber ball — inspiring a module that 'floats' inside the case. He has said he tossed prototypes from a bathroom window to test them.",
      "Orient is no scrappy outsider: since 2017 it's been part of Seiko Epson, with movements built at Akita Epson in Japan. Yet it deliberately stays in the value lane, offering genuine in-house automatics (like the F6922, hacking + hand-winding) at prices that embarrass much of the competition.",
      "Watch the regulation marketing carefully: Seiko 5 / Prospex 4R movements typically run ~+/-25 to +/-45 sec/day from the factory, while Grand Seiko's 9F quartz (special-aging crystal, twin-pulse motor) targets ~+/-10 sec/year — a reminder that 'Japanese quartz' spans the cheapest and the most precise watches made.",
      "The Quartz Crisis cuts both ways in collector lore: Japan 'won' the timekeeping war so completely that it inadvertently pushed Switzerland into the high-mechanical luxury identity it has today. Many enthusiasts argue the modern mechanical-watch renaissance exists because Seiko nearly killed it.",
    ],
